1. Diuturni: i.e. ever since 52 B-C., when Cicero, mourning the loss of his former prestige, had resolved never again to speak in the senate. In course of time he repented of his decision, and waited only for a suitable chance to show publiely his acquiescence in the new state of affairs. — silenti: construe with finem.—-eram usus: we should expect sum usus, but sometimes Latin uses the plupersect to express an action just completed. 2. timore, dolore, verecundia: abl. of cause. 6. mo· dum: moderationem. 12.- Dolebam: explanatory of dolore, l. 2. 13· cum: concessive. 14. nec . . . ducebam: explanatory of vere· cundia, l. 2. 15. versari: while in thought dependent on both, versari follows the construction demanded by fas esse, not that aster persuadere.
